===Etymology===
From northern {{ME.}} dialect ''big'', ''bigge'' ([[powerful]], [[strong]]), of uncertain origin, possibly from a dialect of Old Norse.

===Adjective===
'''big''' (comparative: [[bigger]], superlative: [[biggest]])

#Of a great [[size]]; [[large]]; the weakest sense of great size.
#:''Elephants are '''big''' animals, and they eat a lot.''
#(''colloquial'') [[Adult]].
#:''Kids should get help from '''big''' people if they want to use the kitchen.''
#[[important|Important]] or [[significant]].
#:''What's so '''big''' about that?  I do it all the time.''

===Title===
'''Big''', is a title given to a person, which denotes the fact that they have a degree of cult status. Used in the same way as the words 'Sir' or 'Doctor', '''Big''' is a title that is bestowed on selected individuals who meet certain criteria; including being of greater than slight-build, having a cult following, and having performed a legendary and universally respected act in their chosen profession on a regular basis. The title '''Big''' is generally bestowed on someone by the general public, and their newly acquired title catches on and comes into common usage.

The title of '''Big''' is not like a life peerage or a knighthood, it can be retracted if the recipient no-longer fulfils the requirements; an example of this would be if the recipient of the title were to no longer retain their previously acquired cult following.

